1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,000
We've talked about how there's three factors of authentication, authentication by knowledge,

2
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:47,000
authentication by ownership, and authentication by characteristic. Let's dig into authentication by characteristics,

3
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:54,000
otherwise commonly known as biometric systems. There's actually two major types of authentication by characteristic,

4
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:59,000
which is in fact why we call it authentication by characteristic and not just biometric systems,

5
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:06,000
because the two primary types of authentication by characteristic is physiological and behavioral.

6
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:12,000
Physiological is our physiology, what makes you up, your fingerprints, your hand prints, your iris, your retina.

7
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:19,000
This is your physiology, it's what makes you up. Behavioral, on the other hand, is how you behave,

8
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:25,000
how you talk, how you walk, how you type. So when you hear authentication by characteristic,

9
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:31,000
these are the two major characteristics that you're looking at, physiological and behavioral.

10
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Now, before we get into the actual different types of biometric systems, we first have to talk about

11
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:43,000
a couple of the major considerations related to biometric systems. The first is processing speed.

12
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:49,000
Some of these biometric systems can be a lot slower than a regular system where you just type in a password

13
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:53,000
or something like that, and the system almost instantly knows whether that's the correct password.

14
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:59,000
Some of these biometric systems can take a fair amount of time to scan, which leads directly to the next

15
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:05,000
consideration, which is user acceptance. How willing are users to accept this biometric system?

16
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Especially some of them, like we're going to talk about in a moment here, iris-based systems, where you have to put your

17
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:15,000
eye up to this gummy gross cup, you get a super bright light flash in your eye like I'm in front of right now,

18
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:21,000
and it's a little bit uncomfortable for the user, and so the user acceptance of those types of systems can be fairly low.

19
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:28,000
And then the final, and frankly, this is the most important consideration, is the protection of the biometric data.

20
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:33,000
So we only have one set of fingerprints, one hand print, one iris, one vein pattern.

21
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:39,000
If that data is exposed, if it's out there, there's no way that we can create a new set of fingerprints, a new iris.

22
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:44,000
And so it's extremely important that we protect biometric data.

23
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:49,000
The final consideration that we're going to talk about is accuracy of biometric systems.

24
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:55,000
And before we, there's actually two different error rates, but before we get into those, we have to talk about a very important concept.

25
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,000
And that is that biometric systems are not binary.

26
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,000
What do I mean by that?

27
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:06,000
Well, with the other authentication characteristics like authentication by knowledge or ownership,

28
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:13,000
the system can be 100% sure that that is your password, or 100% sure that that isn't your password.

29
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:16,000
The same is not true with biometric systems.

30
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:21,000
And we've all experienced this with our iPhones where we'll go to unlock the phone with our thumb or our finger,

31
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:26,000
and it won't work because our finger is a little bit dirty or wet or greasy or something.

32
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:32,000
And so we have these error rates in biometric systems, they're not 100% accurate, they're not 100% in binary.

33
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:35,000
So let's talk about these two different error rates.

34
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:40,000
The first is known as a type one false reject error.

35
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:46,000
And what that means is that a valid user is falsely rejected from getting into the system.

36
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:52,000
So this is where a valid user tries to authenticate themselves, and the system says, not allowed, you're rejected.

37
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:54,000
So that's a type one error.

38
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:58,000
A type two error is essentially the exact opposite, the inverse.

39
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:03,000
A type two error is known as a false acceptance error.

40
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:08,000
It's where an invalid user is falsely accepted into the system.

41
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:14,000
In other words, some baddy, some person that shouldn't be getting into the system was allowed into the system.

42
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
That's a type two error.

43
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:19,000
So which is worse, type one or type two?

44
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:24,000
Absolutely, type two, it means type one is just a user being irritated, stupid thing doesn't work.

45
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:29,000
Type two is you're letting an attacker into your system very bad.

46
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:34,000
Now what's interesting about these two error rates is they're inverse to each other.

47
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:41,000
As you try and reduce, for instance, the number of type one errors, you're going to start to increase the number of type two errors, or the same thing in the other direction.

48
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:46,000
As you try and reduce the number of type two errors, the number of type one errors are going to go up.

49
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:49,000
And if you were to graph this, it would look something like this.

50
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:54,000
As your type one errors go down, your type two errors are going to go up.

51
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Now there's a particular spot on this graph that's of interest to us.

52
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
And it's where these lines intersect.

53
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
And we call this a rather absolute name thing.

54
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:05,000
We call it the cross over error rate.

55
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:11,000
And the cross over error rate is essentially a measure of how accurate is the biometric system overall.

56
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:21,000
So this is a really important measurement of if you're evaluating different biometric systems, the cross over error rate will help you identify a system that is overall fairly accurate.

57
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:24,000
And this is also a great example of a hotspot question.

58
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:26,000
So I'll put that one out there.

59
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Now let's look at the types of actual types of biometric systems.

60
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:33,000
And we're going to start with the physiological ones.

61
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:35,000
And most of these are pretty obvious as to what they are.

62
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:37,000
So finger print scanners.

63
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:38,000
What do they look at?

64
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:39,000
A mere finger print.

65
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:40,000
Hand geometry.

66
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:43,000
This is where it looks at the actual geometry of your hand.

67
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:46,000
You always see these ones in the movies because they look like super cool right.

68
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,000
The scanner is going by a green screen.

69
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:50,000
It looks awesome, right?

70
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Be very rarely see these in real life.

71
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
So the next type is known as vascular pattern.

72
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:59,000
Vascular pattern systems look at the vein pattern, usually on the back of your hand.

73
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:03,000
And in fact, most of you are going to see this when you go and sit the CISSP exam.

74
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:08,000
When you get checked into a Pearson View Testing Center, they will actually, as part of the check-in process,

75
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
they'll scan your hand, the back of your hand.

76
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:15,000
And the reason they do that is not because they know your vascular pattern ahead of time,

77
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:19,000
but so that if you decide to take a break, they want to make sure that it's you coming back into the room

78
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:22,000
and not someone that you've paid to take the test for you.

79
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:24,000
So that's a vascular pattern system.

80
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:27,000
And the next is facial. They obviously look at your face.

81
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:30,000
A lot of modern smartphones do that nowadays.

82
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:32,000
Next is iris.

83
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:37,000
So the iris is obviously part of the eye, but what part of the eye?

84
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:40,000
Well, the iris is actually the colored ring around our eye.

85
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:45,000
So the brown, green, the blue, that part of our eye, the colored ring, that is our iris.

86
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And iris-based biometric systems look obviously at the iris.

87
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:55,000
And the final type of physiological-based biometric system is retina.

88
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:58,000
And retina, again, part of your eyeball, but which part?

89
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:01,000
Well, your retina is actually the back of your eyeball.

90
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:06,000
And what retina-based systems are looking at is actually the vane pattern on the back of your eye.

91
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:12,000
And so if you ever get a question or if you're wondering what is the most accurate type of biometric system,

92
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:15,000
the answer is absolutely retina-based systems.

93
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:18,000
And yet, you see them very rarely out in the real world.

94
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,000
And the reason for that is a couple of things.

95
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:22,000
One, users hate them.

96
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:23,000
I've used these systems a few times.

97
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,000
You walk up to this gummy, gross rubber cup.

98
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:26,000
You put it up to your eye.

99
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:29,000
A super bright light is flash in your eye, so you're now blinded.

100
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:32,000
It's very unpleasant to use these systems.

101
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:35,000
And they have some pretty big privacy-related issues.

102
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:39,000
You can tell, for instance, if someone has diabetes, you can tell if they're pregnant or not.

103
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:43,000
So that's a bit of concern from a privacy perspective.

104
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:47,000
So retina-based systems, very accurate, but they have some big downsides.

105
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:51,000
So those are all the physiological-based.

106
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:53,000
Now let's look at the behavioral-based systems.

107
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:55,000
And this is obviously how we behave.

108
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:59,000
So things like voice, how we speak, signature, how we write,

109
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,000
keystroke, how we type.

110
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:05,000
And another one that maybe should be included here as well is gate, how we walk.

111
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:08,000
Gate-based biometric systems are becoming very commonly used.

112
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:12,000
And they actually watch how someone walks past a camera system.

113
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:14,000
And they've been found to be quite accurate.

114
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:19,000
So those are all the authentication methods by Characteristic.

